"Balghouthi M., Chahbani M.H., Guizani A.","Solar powered air conditioning as a solution to reduce environmental pollution in Tunisia",2005,"Desalination","185","1-3",,"105","110",,,10.1016/j.desal.2005.03.073,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-29144443852&partnerID=40&md5=309f2f3197a9f774da8082b3d003c555","Institut National de Recherche Scientifique et Technique, Laboratoire des Applications Solaires, B.P.95, 2050 Hammam-Lif, Tunisia","Balghouthi, M., Institut National de Recherche Scientifique et Technique, Laboratoire des Applications Solaires, B.P.95, 2050 Hammam-Lif, Tunisia; Chahbani, M.H., Institut National de Recherche Scientifique et Technique, Laboratoire des Applications Solaires, B.P.95, 2050 Hammam-Lif, Tunisia; Guizani, A., Institut National de Recherche Scientifique et Technique, Laboratoire des Applications Solaires, B.P.95, 2050 Hammam-Lif, Tunisia","In Tunisia, during the summer, the demand for electricity greatly increases because of the extensive use of air-conditioning systems. This is a source of major problems in the country's electricity supply and contributes to an increase of CO2 emissions causing the environmental pollution and global warming. On the other hand, vapor compression air conditioning systems have impacts on stratospheric ozone depletion because of the chlorofluorocarbons (CFC) and the hydrofluorocarbon (HCFC) refrigerants. The use of solar energy to drive cooling cycles is attractive since the cooling load is roughly in phase with solar energy availability. To cool with solar thermal energy, one solution is to use an absorption chillier using water and lithium bromide solution. In this study we present a project aims at assessing the feasibility of solar powered absorption cooling technology under Tunisian conditions. A simulation with the TRNSYS program is carried out in order to select and size the different components of the solar machine to be installed (collectors, storage tank, heat exchangers...). © 2005 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Absorption; Air conditioning; Lithium bromide; Solar","Air pollution control; Carbon dioxide; Chlorofluorocarbons; Computer simulation; Electric power systems; Electric utilities; Environmental protection; Global warming; Lithium compounds; Ozone layer; Refrigerants; Solar energy; Hydrofluorocarbon; Solar power air conditioning; Tunisia; Air conditioning; adsorption; air conditioning; solar power",,,,,,"Données climatiques de base pour le dimensionnement des installations de chauffage et de refroidissement (2003), Agence Nationale des Energies Renouvenables de Tunisie JanvierLi, Z.F., Sumathy, K., Technology development in the solar absorption air-conditioning systems (2000) Renewable Sustainable Energy Rev., 4, pp. 267-293; (1988) ASHRAE Equipment Handbook, , American Society of Heating Refrigerating and Air-conditioning Engineers, Altanta, GA, USA; Florides, G.A., Kalogirou, S.A., Tassou, S.A., Wrobel, L.C., Modelling and simulation of an absorption solar cooling system for Cyprus (2002) Solar Energy, 72 (1), pp. 43-51; Herold, K.E., Radermacher, R., Klein, S.A., (1996) Absorption Chillers and Heat Pumps, , Book 329 pages, CRS Press LLC, 2000 N.W. Corporate Blvd., Boca Raton, Florida 33431. International Standard Book Number 0-8493-9427-9. Library of congress Card Number 95-45325. Printed in the USA, ref 34567890; Florides, G.A., Kalogirou, S.A., Tassou, S.A., Wrobel, L.C., Modelling and simulation and warming impact assessement of a domestic-size an absorption solar cooling system (2002) Appl. Thermal. Engineering, 22, pp. 1313-1325; Elsafty, A., Al-Daini, A.J., Economical comparison between a solar-powered vapour absorption air-conditioning system and a vapour compression system in the Middle East (2002) Renewable Energy, 25, pp. 569-583","Balghouthi, M.; Institut National de Recherche Scientifique et Technique, Laboratoire des Applications Solaires, B.P.95, 2050 Hammam-Lif, Tunisia; email: balghouthi_moncef@yahoo.fr",,,,,,